{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-lesson-template-js","path":"/low-level/hex","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<p>The phrase <em>machine code</em> is often used when describing low-level programming and it conjours images of engineers reading pages of ones and zeroes. In reality, most humans would be unable to follow endless blocks of ones and zeroes thus <em>hexadecimal</em> serves as an intermediate step: concise enough for machines but readable enough for humans and is the lowest level programming language.</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Note: I don't expect you to memorize how to read hexadecimal. This is more of an FYI because Web Assembly error and opcodes are often presented in hex.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Hexadecimal uses Base 16 for calculating byte values and the letters A through F represent the numbers 10 through 15 respectively.</p>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>Decimal</th>\n<th>Hexadecimal</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>0</td>\n<td>00</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>1</td>\n<td>01</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>2</td>\n<td>02</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>..</td>\n<td>..</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>9</td>\n<td>09</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10</td>\n<td>0A</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>11</td>\n<td>0B</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>12</td>\n<td>0C</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>13</td>\n<td>0D</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>14</td>\n<td>0E</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>15</td>\n<td>0F</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>16</td>\n<td>10</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>17</td>\n<td>11</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>18</td>\n<td>12</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; max-width: 800px; \"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/intro-to-web-assembly/static/3b96b0fc9dc83cd9f3c46c2fa10568b7/63ec5/hex.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 54.49999999999999%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"hex\"\n        title=\"hex\"\n        src=\"/intro-to-web-assembly/static/3b96b0fc9dc83cd9f3c46c2fa10568b7/5a190/hex.png\"\n        srcset=\"/intro-to-web-assembly/static/3b96b0fc9dc83cd9f3c46c2fa10568b7/772e8/hex.png 200w,\n/intro-to-web-assembly/static/3b96b0fc9dc83cd9f3c46c2fa10568b7/e17e5/hex.png 400w,\n/intro-to-web-assembly/static/3b96b0fc9dc83cd9f3c46c2fa10568b7/5a190/hex.png 800w,\n/intro-to-web-assembly/static/3b96b0fc9dc83cd9f3c46c2fa10568b7/63ec5/hex.png 812w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p><code class=\"language-text\">2E7</code> = 743<br>\n(<strong>256</strong> * 2) + (<strong>16</strong> * 14) + (<strong>1</strong> * 7) = 743</p>\n<p>Confused? Totally ok! The first time coming across hex may seem a bit daunting but it's easy to see the advantage of hex when it comes to brevity and readabilty as compared with binary.</p>\n<p><code class=\"language-text\">1A7</code> = 423<br>\n<code class=\"language-text\">110100111</code> = 423</p>\n<p>I've found this <a href=\"https://www.bbc.co.uk/bitesize/guides/z3fgcdm/revision/2\">site</a> by the BBC useful for understanding hexadecimal.</p>\n<h4 id=\"exercise\" style=\"position:relative;\"><a href=\"#exercise\" aria-label=\"exercise permalink\" class=\"anchor before\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Exercise</h4>\n<details>\n  <summary>What number does 1F7 represent?</summary>\n<p><code class=\"language-text\">503</code><br>\n(<strong>256</strong> * 1) + (<strong>16</strong> * 15) + (<strong>1</strong> * 7) = 503</p>\n</details>","frontmatter":{"path":"/low-level/hex","title":"Hexadecimal","order":"1D","section":"Low Level Stuff","description":""}},"allMarkdownRemark":{"edges":[{"node":{"frontmatter":{"order":"0B","path":"/intro-to-wasm","title":"Introduction to Web Assembly"}}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"order":"5A","path":"/closing","title":"In closing"}}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"order":"3A","path":"/assembly-script","title":"What is AssemblyScript"}}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"order":"0A","path":"/intro","title":"Hello"}}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"order":"3G","path":"/assembly-script/imports","title":"Imports"}}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"order":"3K","path":"/assembly-script/jsvwasm","title":"JS vs Wasm"}}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"order":"3H","path":"/assembly-script/loader","title":"AssemblyScript Loader"}}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"order":"3F","path":"/assembly-script/loading-browser","title":"Loading AssemblyScript - Browser"}}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"order":"3E","path":"/assembly-script/loading-node","title":"Loading AssemblyScript - NodeJS"}}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"order":"3J","path":"/assembly-script/memory","title":"Memory"}}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"order":"3C","path":"/assembly-script/setup","title":"AssemblyScript Setup"}}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"order":"3I","path":"/assembly-script/loader-usage","title":"Using the AssemblyScript loader"}}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"order":"3D","path":"/assembly-script/writing","title":"Writing AssemblyScript"}}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"order":"1C","path":"/low-level/binary-contd","title":"Binary continued"}}},{"node":{"frontmatter":{"order":"1B","pa